<HEADLINE>
<P>
GORMAN MAN, 34, HELD ON SUSPICION OF ARSON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Gorman-area man was being held on suspicion of arson Tuesday for setting a 
small grass fire on a neighbor's property after a dispute, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles County sheriff's arson investigators arrested Robert Jordan, 34, at 
his home Monday near 250th Street West and Avenue A in the sparsely populated 
northwest Antelope Valley. 
</P>
<P>
Jordan allegedly used a cigarette lighter Saturday afternoon to set a fire that 
burned a quarter of an acre of grass on property containing a house and a feed 
store near 250th Street West and Avenue C-15, deputies said. 
</P>
<P>
The fire, which residents extinguished before firefighters arrived, bore little 
resemblance to a spate of suspicious brush fires this month in the Antelope and 
Santa Clarita valleys. Jordan is not a suspect in any other fires, authorities 
said. 
</P>
<P>
The owner of the house and feed store told firefighters that the fire was set 
by his neighbor after an argument, county Fire Capt. Michael Glosson said. 
Deputies acting on a tip later arrested Jordan, who was being held in lieu of 
$20,000 bail at the Antelope Valley sheriff's station. 
</P>
</TEXT>
