<P>
HEALTH; 
</P>
<P>
TREATMENT FOR HEPATITIS B FOUND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FROM TIMES WIRE SERVICES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BOSTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Interferon is the first treatment to relieve and even cure lingering hepatitis 
B infections, the leading cause of cirrhosis and liver cancer and one of the 
world's biggest killers, researchers have found. 
</P>
<P>
A study to appear in Thursday's New England Journal of Medicine found that 
injections of the natural protein can stop the hepatitis B virus from 
destroying the liver in almost half of the patients who are chronically 
infected. One in 10 is cured. 
</P>
<P>
Until now, there has been no treatment for the hepatitis B virus. While 
interferon clearly does not help everyone, having any therapy at all is 
considered to be an important step in controlling this infection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
