<P>
ENQUIRING MINDS PREEMPTED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FROM TIMES WIRE SERVICES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Joan Lunden says she is not leaving "Good Morning America," getting a divorce 
or even having an alien's baby. 
</P>
<P>
Lunden told viewers of ABC's morning show all this Tuesday after she said 
National Enquirer reporters were asking her colleagues if she seems troubled 
lately. 
</P>
<P>
"It was a preemptive strike," she said afterward. "I told them I could either 
do that or just be a wimp and sit back and let them make up whatever they want 
and print it." 
</P>
<P>
Ian Calder, editor of the tabloid in Lantana, Fla., said the queries about 
Lunden concerned problems her husband, a TV producer, has had with lawsuits 
over production bills for "Everyday," a syndicated program on which Lunden is 
host. 
</P>
<P>
"As far as I know, this was just something we were checking out and we've no 
plans to run a story," Calder said. 
</P>
